For a good smoothie, you always need a good base to make the smoothie have a creamy texture. My favorites are banana, avocado, and green yogurt (beware of flavored yogurts, they are loaded with added sugars). You can also blend with water to avoid adding calories.
My favorite additional fruits to put in smoothies are berries (low in calories too), mango and peaches, but any fruit you like will work.
Experiment with adding vegetables and / or greens to your smoothies. For example, my favorite smoothie recipe calls for banana, lemon juice, mango, peaches, cucumber, spinach, ginger and turmeric. It’s extremely low calorie and you can hardly taste the veggies. Such a great way to sneak those in through out the day!
You can also experiment with other ingredients such as oats or nut butter. My second favorite smoothie recipe calls for coffee, banana, oatmeal, pb fit protein powder, and cocoa powder. It literally taste like a chocolate shake!

I have been watching Suits.  I feel like at the start, writers couldn't make up whether they wanted to focus the show on Mike's super ability or the lawyers. I feel like Mike using his superpower was the hook that got us interested and should have been used way more in the show. Also, at times, it felt like they were undecided whether they wanted this to be a comedy or a drama.
The premise of their "lawyering" is basically "hey you owe me this, do this for me" and around the circle the same every time. And someone always had an ace in their sleeve, but they kept it for way too long, just use it and be done with it. How were they actually solving any of the cases while there was so much internal drama going around... Real law was bent so hard to fit the show, but I don't mind that part, it didn't take away from the story, they made it believable. There were no lawyer's deaths or judge's, which happen way more often in real life, that would have made the show more realistic. Mike going to prison made me interested in the show once again, I liked that season the most probably. Later down the road once Mike and Rachel left, I still enjoyed the show, didn't miss them one bit to be honest.

messages.content:
When it comes to heat protectants with keratin, there are quite a few options. It's great that you're looking into keratin-infused products as keratin helps strengthen and repair hair, especially with heat styling. For specific product recommendations, I suggest looking for reputable brands that specialize in hair care, as they often have well-researched formulas. Checking reviews, especially from people with similar hair types, can also be helpful.
The frequency of using keratin products depends on your hair type and condition. If you have damaged or color-treated hair, you might benefit from more frequent use. However, for normal hair, using a keratin heat protectant each time you apply heat can be sufficient. It's important to maintain a balance, as too much keratin can make hair stiff and brittle. If you notice your hair feeling hard or less elastic, it might be good to reduce the frequency. Consider alternating between keratin and non-keratin heat protectants to maintain balance.

You see, the low "self-worth" that you're feeling is not because you're not handsome enough, rich enough, or have enough friends. It is because you keep lying to yourself everyday.
Confidence doesn't come from your external experiences but the internal ones you tell yourself.
If you tell yourself that you'll go to the gym and you do it, you become slightly more confident.

These are my tips and tricks I have been using for a while now:
Cold, cool, or lukewarm showers are the best; they don't dry out your skin and actually can leave it refreshed. Also, this is great for your hair to make it shiny and silky.
If you wear makeup, WASH IT OFF EVERY NIGHT. No exceptions to this one.
Instead of lotion, I use liquid coconut oil to moisturize after a shower. It has helped my KP more than any dermatologist, keeps it silky smooth and touchable, moisturizes like mad, and leaves a light sweet scent. If you can't find coconut oil, look for tubs of Eucerin. It is sent from the skin gods, though expensive.
For a face scrub since I have dry skin, I mix raw sugar with coconut oil and a bit of honey. Rinse and pat dry with a clean towel. I don't know if I'd suggest this for someone with oily skin, though.
Something a lot of people don't do because of the extra time it takes is PAT DRY with a dry towel after you step out of the shower. Rubbing can scrape your skin in ways it shouldn't be. Within 3 minutes of patting dry, apply moisturizer all over. The moisturizer locks in the water on the outer layers of your skin; it doesn't normally put more in. After about three minutes, all that good ole' H2O evaporates.

I really like soaking hot spring baths, they’re not very pricey, but I no longer live in a place where that’s possible. That’s the best for just relaxing.
Now for spas I just go to get laser hair removal (legs and butt, underarms, lower face), and occasionally eyebrow-waxing. I greatly resent the time I spend shaving my legs etc so it’s nice to be working towards not needing to do that, and the growth is always extra delayed/stopped for the next 8 weeks after the treatment. I find that very worth it! In 5 treatments over 1.5 years, I’ve seen a permanent 60-75% reduction in hair follicle presence in treated areas.
The eyebrow waxing treatment is nice too—I like seeing the immediate effect of that.

messages.content: New Mexico has a nice variety of both developed and undeveloped springs. Ojo Caliente, north of Santa Fe is my favorite, but they recently had a fire and I’m not sure if it has reopened. They have a sister property south of Santa Fe that looks nice. Both properties have lodging and spa amenities. Giggling Springs in in Jemez Springs are an easy day trip from Albuquerque. By far I think the best hot springs in Colorado are Pagosa Springs. Stay on the property; it’s worth the splurge!

I recently visited the natural hot springs in Mammoth CA (Wild Willey's, Crab Cooker, Whitmore Hot Tub) and it was one of the most relaxing/rejuvenating experiences. I was working remotely up there and had incredible mental clarity and energy after spending my mornings soaking for a week. Now I'm hooked haha.
Doing research for my next trip, I discovered that around the world there are all these epic luxury resorts, built on hot springs that I had no idea they existed. Especially in Europe and Japan it looks like they are super into it. Aqua Dome in Austria looks insaneee.
